JPA (Java Persistence API), now officially known as Jakarta Persistence, is a Java specification that simplifies object-relational mapping (ORM) 
by allowing developers to map Java classes (entities) to database tables using annotations rather than writing complex SQL. 
It acts as a standardized framework that defines what persistence operations must exist, while leaving the implementation details to providers like 
Hibernate or EclipseLink. 
Key characteristics of JPA include:
Portability: Code written using JPA can run across different databases without modification, as the specification separates the API from the underlying implementation. 
Core Concepts: It utilizes the EntityManager as the primary interface for managing persistence, handling CRUD operations, transactions, and queries 
via JPQL (Jakarta Persistence Query Language). 
Evolution: Originally released as version 1.0 in 2006, the specification was renamed to Jakarta Persistence in 2019, with the latest versions (3.2) 
targeting inclusion in Jakarta EE 11. 
JPA is distinct from Hibernate, which is an implementation of the JPA specification, and Spring Data JPA, which provides a higher-level repository 
abstraction built on top of JPA to further reduce boilerplate code.  While JDBC remains the low-level standard for direct SQL execution, JPA is widely 
preferred in enterprise applications for its ability to abstract relational 
data management within an object-oriented paradigm.
pom.xml is the Project Object Model (POM) file, the central configuration file for a Maven project, written in XML and located at the project's root directory. 
It serves as a one-stop-shop for all project information and build configuration. 
